<subSubSection pageNumber="715" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="715">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="715">Note:</emphasis>
Wijnands (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="715">Bot. Commelins</emphasis>
: 84. 1981) argued that the typification by Roessler should be rejected because the thesis in which the Linnaean name was published was based largely on specimens lent to Linnaeus by Burman. While this is, in general, true, 1027.3 (LINN) is annotated as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Othonna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rigens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="715">Othonna rigens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Linnaeus, and appears to be original material for both this name and 
<taxonomicName authority="(L.) L. (1763)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1763" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gorteria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rigens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="715">Gorteria rigens</emphasis>
(L.) L. (1763)
</taxonomicName>
. Consequently, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Roessler’s">Roessler's</normalizedToken>
typification is accepted here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
